To list instances in Google Compute Engine using the Node.js client library, you can use the `compute.instances.list` method. Here's a basic example:

First, make sure you have the `google-cloud` npm package installed:

```bash
npm install @google-cloud/compute
```

Then, you can use the following Node.js code to list instances:

```javascript
const { Compute } = require('@google-cloud/compute');
const compute = new Compute();

async function listInstances() {
  const projectId = 'YOUR_PROJECT_ID'; // Replace with your project ID

  // Get the default zone for the specified project
  const [zones] = await compute.getZones({ projectId });
  const zone = zones[0].name;

  // List the instances in the specified project and zone
  const [instances] = await compute.getVMs({ projectId, zone });

  console.log('Instances:');
  instances.forEach(instance => {
    console.log(`- ${instance.name}`);
  });
}

listInstances();
```

Replace `'YOUR_PROJECT_ID'` with your actual Google Cloud project ID. This code retrieves the default zone for the specified project and then lists the instances in that project and zone.

Make sure your Google Cloud credentials are set up properly. You can either set the `GOOGLE_APPLICATION_CREDENTIALS` environment variable to the path of your service account key file or use `compute.auth` to authenticate programmatically.

```javascript
// Authenticate programmatically (if not using GOOGLE_APPLICATION_CREDENTIALS)
await compute.auth.getClient();
```

Remember to handle errors and edge cases appropriately in a production environment.

