To start a VM with a specific image using the Google Cloud Compute Engine Node.js client library, you can use the `compute.instances.insert` method. Here's a basic example:

First, make sure you have the `google-cloud` npm package installed:

```bash
npm install @google-cloud/compute
```

Then, you can use the following Node.js code to start a VM with a specific image:

```javascript
const { Compute } = require('@google-cloud/compute');
const compute = new Compute();

async function startVM() {
  const projectId = 'YOUR_PROJECT_ID'; // Replace with your project ID
  const zone = 'us-central1-a'; // Replace with your desired zone
  const vmName = 'my-vm'; // Replace with your desired VM name
  const machineType = 'n1-standard-1'; // Replace with your desired machine type
  const sourceImage = 'projects/debian-cloud/global/images/debian-9-stretch-v20220329'; // Replace with your desired image

  // Define the VM configuration
  const vmConfig = {
    project: projectId,
    zone: zone,
    resource: {
      name: vmName,
      machineType: `zones/${zone}/machineTypes/${machineType}`,
      disks: [
        {
          boot: true,
          initializeParams: {
            sourceImage: sourceImage,
          },
        },
      ],
      networkInterfaces: [
        {
          network: 'global/networks/default',
          accessConfigs: [
            {
              name: 'external-nat',
              type: 'ONE_TO_ONE_NAT',
            },
          ],
        },
      ],
    },
  };

  // Start the VM
  const [vm] = await compute.createVM(vmConfig);

  console.log(`VM ${vm.name} created.`);
}

startVM();
```

Replace the placeholder values with your actual project ID, desired zone, VM name, machine type, and source image. The `sourceImage` should be in the format `'projects/PROJECT_ID/global/images/IMAGE_NAME'`.

Make sure your Google Cloud credentials are set up properly. You can either set the `GOOGLE_APPLICATION_CREDENTIALS` environment variable to the path of your service account key file or use `compute.auth` to authenticate programmatically.

```javascript
// Authenticate programmatically (if not using GOOGLE_APPLICATION_CREDENTIALS)
await compute.auth.getClient();
```

This code creates a VM with the specified configuration, including the specified image, and starts the VM. Remember to handle errors and edge cases appropriately in a production environment.

